Northwind Traders Sales Analysis

  • Author: Andy Wang, Johns Hopkins University, Class of 2027
  • Github Repository: https://github.com/sirandy3000/projects/tree/master/northwind

Scenario

In this project, I assume the role of Data Analyst at Northwind Traders, an international gourmet food distributor. Management is looking to you for insights to make strategic decisions in several aspects of the business. The projects focus on:

  • Evaluating employee performance to boost productivity,
  • Understanding product sales and category performance to optimize inventory and marketing strategies,
  • Analyzing sales growth to identify trends, monitor company progress, and make more accurate forecasts,
  • And evaluating customer purchase behavior to target high-value customers with promotional incentives.

To achieve these goals, I use PL/pgSQL to analyze the Northwind PostgreSQL database. I compose complex queries using such techniques as window functions and CTEs, and I create views and stored functions to aid the analysis. I then use the retrieved data to create elegant visualizations using ggplot2, providing essential insights to management and contributing significantly to the companys strategic decisions.

Note: from here on, text within the scenario is bolded.

1. Database Setup/Connection

I use the DBI and RPostgres libraries as a backend to execute all SQL statements/queries in this notebook against the Northwind database on my local PostgreSQL server. To copy this database onto any PostgreSQL server, use the northwind.sql file found in this repository.

library(DBI)
library(ggplot2)
library(patchwork)
library(RPostgres)
library(scales)
library(tibble)

conn <- DBI::dbConnect(
  RPostgres::Postgres(),
  dbname = "northwind",
  host = "localhost",
  user = "postgres",
  password = password,
  port = 5432
)

I first created a function to list all the tables and views in the current database.

dbExecute(conn, paste(
  "CREATE FUNCTION show_tables() RETURNS TABLE (",
    "name information_schema.sql_identifier,",
    "type information_schema.character_data",
  ") LANGUAGE plpgsql AS $$ BEGIN RETURN QUERY",
  "SELECT table_name, table_type",
  "FROM information_schema.tables",
  "WHERE table_schema = 'public' AND table_type IN ('BASE TABLE', 'VIEW')",
  "ORDER BY 1; END $$;"
))

I then created a function to list all the columns of a given table, along with their data types and whether null values are allowed.

dbExecute(conn, paste(
  "CREATE FUNCTION describe_table(table_name_ varchar) RETURNS TABLE (",
    "variable information_schema.sql_identifier,",
    "type information_schema.character_data,",
    "nullable information_schema.yes_or_no",
  ") LANGUAGE plpgsql AS $$ BEGIN RETURN QUERY",
  "SELECT column_name, data_type, is_nullable",
  "FROM information_schema.columns",
  "WHERE table_name = table_name_",
  "ORDER BY 1; END $$;"
))
as_tibble(dbGetQuery(conn, "SELECT * FROM show_tables();"))

3. Ranking Employee Sales Performance

As the lead Data Analyst at Northwind Traders, youve been tasked with comprehensively reviewing the companys sales performance from an employee perspective. The objective is twofold:

  • First, the management team wants to recognize and reward top-performing employees, fostering a culture of excellence within the organization.
  • Second, they want to identify employees who might be struggling so that they can offer the necessary training or resources to help them improve.

The management team is keen on encouraging healthy competition and rewarding stellar performers. Theyve asked you to rank employees based on their total sales amount, then compare each employees sales performance to the average sales performance of all employees to evaluate their contributions.

I first created a view that stores the total price of each order, appropriately combining unit price, quantity, and possible discounts.

dbExecute(conn, paste(
  "CREATE VIEW order_prices AS",
  "SELECT order_id, product_id, unit_price * quantity * (1 - discount) price",
  "FROM order_details;"
))

I then created a function that concatenates first and last names, stored separately, into full names.

dbExecute(conn, paste(
  "CREATE FUNCTION full_name(first_name varchar, last_name varchar)",
  "RETURNS varchar LANGUAGE plpgsql AS $$ BEGIN",
  "RETURN (SELECT first_name || ' ' || last_name); END $$;"
))
df_3 <- as_tibble(dbGetQuery(conn, paste(
  "WITH employee_totals AS (",
    "SELECT last_name, first_name, SUM(COALESCE(price, 0)) total",
    "FROM employees LEFT JOIN orders USING (employee_id)",
      "INNER JOIN order_prices USING (order_id)",
    "GROUP BY employee_id, 1, 2",
  ")",
  "SELECT full_name(first_name, last_name), total::int total_sales,",
    "RANK() OVER (ORDER BY total DESC) sales_rank,",
    "(total - (SELECT AVG(total) FROM employee_totals)) /",
      "(SELECT AVG(total) FROM employee_totals) pct_compared_to_avg",
  "FROM employee_totals ORDER BY 3, 1;"
)))

4. Running Total of Monthly Sales

Having completed the employee performance ranking, youve provided the management team with valuable insights into individual employee contributions. Theyre now keen on gaining a more macro-level perspective, specifically around the companys overall sales performance over time. Theyre looking to visualize the progress of the sales and identify trends that might shape the companys future strategies.

Your first task in this new analysis is to visualize the companys sales progress over time on a monthly basis. This will involve aggregating the sales data at a monthly level and calculating a running total of sales by month. This visual will provide the management team with a clear depiction of sales trends and help identify periods of high or low sales activity.

After this, the management team would like to analyze the month-over-month sales growth rate. Understanding the rate at which sales are increasing or decreasing from month to month will help the management team identify significant trends. For this task, youll need to calculate the percentage change in sales from one month to the next.

I first created a function that stores the month in which each order was made.

dbExecute(conn, paste(
  "CREATE VIEW order_months (order_id, month_) AS",
  "SELECT order_id, DATE_TRUNC('month', order_date) FROM orders;"
))
df_4 <- as_tibble(dbGetQuery(conn, paste(
  "WITH monthly_totals AS (",
    "SELECT month_, SUM(price) total",
    "FROM order_months INNER JOIN order_prices USING (order_id)",
    "GROUP BY 1",
  ")",
  "SELECT month_, total::int,",
    "(SUM(total) OVER (ORDER BY month_))::int running_total,",
    "COALESCE((total - LAG(total) OVER (ORDER BY month_)) /",
      "LAG(total) OVER (ORDER BY month_), 0) percent_change",
  "FROM monthly_totals ORDER BY 1;"
)))

fig_4a <-
  ggplot(df_4, aes(month_, running_total)) +

  scale_x_datetime(breaks = "2 months", labels = NULL) +

    breaks = seq(0, 1200000, 200000),

    title = "Top: Cumulative Sales, Bottom: Percent Change by Month",

  ) +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5))

fig_4b <-
  ggplot(df_4, aes(month_, percent_change)) +
  geom_area(color = "blue", fill = "gold") +
  scale_x_datetime(breaks = "2 months", labels = label_date("%Y-%m")) +
  scale_y_continuous(breaks = seq(-0.75, 0.75, 0.25), labels = label_percent()) +
  labs(x = "Month", y = "Percent Change") +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1))

5. Identifying High-Value Customers

Upon completing the sales growth and trend analysis, youve provided the management team valuable insights into the companys sales performance over time. Now, theyre interested in a different, equally important, aspect of the business: the customers.

They want to identify high-value customers to whom they can offer targeted promotions and special offers, which could drive increased sales, improve customer retention, and attract new customers.

To do this, theyve asked you to identify customers with above-average order values. These customers might be businesses buying in bulk or individuals purchasing high-end products.

df_5 <- as_tibble(dbGetQuery(conn, paste(
  "WITH customer_totals AS (",
    "SELECT customer_id, SUM(price) total",
    "FROM orders INNER JOIN order_prices USING (order_id)",
    "GROUP BY 1",
  ")",
  "SELECT contact_name, country, total::int",
  "FROM customers INNER JOIN customer_totals USING (customer_id)",
  "WHERE total > (SELECT AVG(total) FROM customer_totals)",
  "ORDER BY 3 DESC, 1;"
)))

6. Percentage of Sales for Each Category

Having successfully identified customers with above-average order values, youve been asked to switch gears and focus on another critical aspect of the companys operations: product and category performance.

Youve been asked to provide the management team with an understanding of sales composition across different product categories. By knowing the percentage of total sales for each product category, they can gain insights into which categories drive most of the companys sales.

This understanding will help guide decisions about inventory (e.g., which categories should be stocked more heavily) and marketing strategies (e.g., which categories should be promoted more aggressively).

df_6 <- as_tibble(dbGetQuery(conn, paste(
  "WITH category_totals AS (",
    "SELECT category_id, SUM(COALESCE(price, 0)) total",
    "FROM categories LEFT JOIN products USING (category_id)",
      "LEFT JOIN order_prices USING (product_id)",
    "GROUP BY 1",
  ")",
  "SELECT category_name, total sales, total / (SELECT SUM(total) FROM category_totals) pct_of_total",
  "FROM categories INNER JOIN category_totals USING (category_id)",
  "ORDER BY 2 DESC, 1;"
)))

8. Top Products per Category

With the knowledge of sales by category, the next step is to drill down further into each group. The management team wants to know the top three items sold in each product category. This will allow them to identify star performers and ensure that these products are kept in stock and marketed prominently.

df_8 <- as_tibble(dbGetQuery(conn, paste(
  "WITH product_sales AS (",
    "SELECT category_name, product_name, SUM(COALESCE(quantity, 0)) quantity",
    "FROM categories LEFT JOIN products USING (category_id)",
      "INNER JOIN order_details USING (product_id)",
    "GROUP BY 1, 2",
  "), product_ranks AS (",
    "SELECT *, ROW_NUMBER() OVER",
      "(PARTITION BY category_name ORDER BY quantity DESC) rank_",
    "FROM product_sales",
  ")",
  "SELECT category_name, product_name, quantity",
  "FROM product_ranks WHERE rank_ <= 3 ORDER BY 1, 3 DESC;"
)))

print(df_8, n = Inf)

9. Exceptional Products

Identify products that perform exceptionally well in terms of sales. Specifically, products whose total sales exceed the 75th percentile.

I first created a view that stores the percentiles of each product with respect to its total number of sales.

dbExecute(conn, paste(
  "CREATE VIEW product_percentiles AS",
  "WITH product_sales AS (",
    "SELECT product_name, SUM(quantity)::int quantity",
    "FROM products INNER JOIN order_details USING (product_id)",
    "GROUP BY 1",
  ")",
  "SELECT *, CUME_DIST() OVER (ORDER BY quantity) perc",
  "FROM product_sales;"
))

I then created a function that generalizes the solution to an arbitrary percentile p, returning all products whose total sales exceed the p-th percentile.

dbExecute(conn, paste(
  "CREATE FUNCTION products_over_percentile(percentile_ real)",
  "RETURNS TABLE (product varchar, num_sold int, percentile double precision)",
  "LANGUAGE plpgsql AS $$ BEGIN RETURN QUERY",
  "SELECT * FROM product_percentiles",
  "WHERE perc > percentile_ / 100",
  "ORDER BY 3 DESC, 1; END $$;"
))
df_9 <- as_tibble(dbGetQuery(conn, (
  "SELECT * FROM products_over_percentile(75);"
)))
